<section id="guide">
  <div class="section-intro">
    <h2>Buyer's <span>Guide</span></h2>
    <p>Thoughtful answers to the questions every discerning buyer should ask before deciding.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="guide-grid">
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"New builds cost more per sq ft — why not buy older and renovate?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">True on paper, but renovation costs in Naples waterfront are substantial — $300–500/sq ft once you factor permits, impact-resistant upgrades, seawall work, and post-storm contractor demand. A 2017 or 2021 build like 360 Heron or 175 Conners already carries modern codes, impact glass, and updated systems. The renovation premium often exceeds the new-build price gap — and you lose 12–18 months of enjoyment while construction is underway.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"Prices have softened — is now the right moment to buy?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">The market did see inventory rise in 2024–2025, and properties like 1100 Sandpiper (–20.6%) and 175 Conners (down from $7.5M) reflect that adjustment. However, waterfront Gulf-access inventory in Conners is structurally scarce — fixed streets, no new land. A south-facing, move-in-ready home like 360 Heron will find a buyer. The price reductions you're seeing are the deals that have already happened. The question is whether you have a better specific property available right now.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"I'm not a boater — does Gulf access really matter to my return?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">Yes — even if you never put a boat in the water, Gulf access is a core value multiplier in Naples. Homes without it in Conners or Royal Harbor trade at a 20–35% discount. It's infrastructure you pay for once and monetize on exit. The grandfathered covered boathouse at 2290 Tarpon Rd cannot be newly permitted under current regulations — making it genuinely irreplaceable and a strong resale asset.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"Which direction should the pool and backyard face — and why?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">In Southwest Florida, south-facing is the gold standard for pool areas. You get all-day sun from morning through late afternoon without harsh glare, and the pool stays warm year-round — the house doesn't shade the pool in the afternoons either. West-facing (Tarpon Rd and Sandpiper) gives spectacular sunsets but shaded pool mornings. Of the seven listings, 360 Heron, 418 Seabee, and 256 Tradewinds all explicitly confirm south-facing — a premium you feel every day.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"Royal Harbor or Conners — which neighborhood fits my lifestyle better?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">Two distinct lifestyles. Conners/Vanderbilt Beach is beach-resort in character — Ritz-Carlton, Mercato, Delnor-Wiggins State Park, and Vanderbilt Beach are within a mile. It draws a seasonal, recreation-oriented crowd. Royal Harbor feels more rooted — 5th Avenue South, fine dining, the arts scene, and Old Naples character just minutes away. If beach proximity and resort energy come first, Conners wins. If walkable dining, arts, and a more established neighborhood feel matter, Royal Harbor is the stronger fit.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="guide-card">
      <div class="guide-q">"What about hurricane risk and insurance — what should I know?"</div>
      <div class="guide-a">Newer builds have a decisive, quantifiable advantage here. Florida building codes changed materially after Hurricane Andrew and again after the 2004–2005 seasons. Homes built in 2017 or newer carry current wind load standards, impact glass, and reinforced construction — and qualify for lower insurance rates. Tarpon Rd highlighted "no damage from Helene or Milton" because that's the first question any buyer asks about a 2011 build. Request an actual insurance quote on every property — the annual premium difference between a 2011 and 2025 build in AE flood zone can run $30,000–60,000.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

